Here's a structured list of concepts to cover in your LinkedIn post, grouped thematically:

  ---
  The problem / motivation
  - Predicting car prices from mileage — a classic, intuitive real-world regression problem
  - Why linear regression is a great starting point for understanding ML

  The math behind linear regression
  - The hypothesis function: price = θ₀ + θ₁ × km
  - What θ₀ (intercept) and θ₁ (slope) represent
  - The cost function: why we minimize the sum of squared errors

  Gradient descent
  - The core idea: iteratively nudging parameters in the direction that reduces error
  - The role of the learning rate
  - How you tracked convergence by logging MSE per epoch

  Data preprocessing
  - Why raw mileage values (up to 240,000 km) would cause instability during training
  - Z-score normalization: centering and scaling the input
  - The relationship between normalization and gradient descent stability

  Evaluation metrics
  - RSS (Residual Sum of Squares) — raw error signal
  - RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) — interpretable error in price units
  - R² (coefficient of determination) — how much variance the model explains

  Visualization
  - Plotting the regression line against the scatter of actual prices
  - The convergence curve: watching MSE drop over 1000 epochs
  - Density/distribution curve of the normalized input

  Train / predict separation
  - Saving learned parameters (θ₀, θ₁) to a JSON file after training
  - Loading them at prediction time to score new data from a CSV
  - Clean separation of concerns between train.py and predict.py

  Takeaways worth highlighting
  - Building ML from scratch (no sklearn) deepens understanding of what libraries do for you
  - The gap between theory (equations) and implementation (vectorized numpy operations)
  - This is a 42 school project — shows you implemented it without black-box libraries
